<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Nolina </i>is a diverse genus of 25 species in the southwestern United States and Mexico. They are striking tufted, liliaceous shrubs with large panicles of white flowers up to 4 m tall. Four species grow in California (USDA-NRCS 2007b). <i>N. cismontana </i>and <i>N. interrata </i>(CNPS list 1B plants) grow in other alliances in southern California. <br/>
<br/>
<i>Nolina bigelovii </i>and <i>N. parryi </i>form conspicuous groves in southern areas of the state, which we place both in this alliance. Groves of both species associate with stands of the <i>Artemisia tridentata, Pinus monophylla, </i>and other alliances in higher elevation zones of the Mojave Desert, eastern slopes of the Peninsular Ranges, and the southern Sierra Nevada. Stands are highly localized and regularly occur on steep to moderately steep, rocky terrain with bedrock and boulders, where plant cover is about 40% (Thomas et al. 2004). Plants appear to require adequate moisture channeled along cracks in bedrock. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
