    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Mojave Desert</b> (322Aj, Am). Stands of <i>Nolina parryi</i> exist in the Kingston Range and Little San Bernardino Mountains (Thomas et al. 2004). The most extensive are in the Kingston Range, where they occupy the steep granitic slopes with <i>Coleogyne ramosissima</i> scrub and <i>Pinus monophylla</i> woodlands. Small groves of <i>N. bigelovii</i> occur in the Whipple Mountains on igneous and metamorphic rock outcrops.</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada</b> (M261Er, Eu). Small stands of <i>N. parryi</i> on the Kern Plateau occupy granitic outcrops surrounded by <i>Pinus monophylla</i> and <i>P. jeffreyi</i> woodlands.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Bp). Stands of both species exist on the eastern slopes of the Peninsular Ranges. <i>N. bigelovii</i> occurs in the Carrizo Gorge area of the Jacumba Mountains on granitic outcrops; <i>N. bigelovii</i> occurs in the Jacumba Mountains in Anza-Borrego Desert State Park (Spolsky 1979, Keeler-Wolf et al. 1998b) in groves adjacent to stands of <i>Prunus fremontii, Juniperus californica,</i> and <i>Eriogonum fasciculatum</i> alliances with portions subjected to recent fires; and <i>N. parryi</i> occurs on the very steep granitic escarpment west of Palm Springs in the San Jacinto Mountains with similar conditions.</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Stands are typically isolated and localized groves surrounded by one or several other desert scrub alliances. As the mosaic of vegetation becomes subject to frequent fire, the elimination of groves appears more probable. Extensive stands in the Kingston Range occur with mature <i>Coleogyne ramosissima </i>stands, which are associated with long fire intervals. </div>
</div>

    

    

